===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
[[File:京師畯尊-西周早期.jpg|thumb|Jingshijun Zun 京師畯尊, Early Western Zhou period]]
{{och-l|漢|tr=*n̥ˤar}}: semantic {{l|zh|水}} (“water”) + phonetic {{och-l|熯|tr=*n̥ˤanʔ}}. Earliest attested in early Western Zhou bronze inscriptions, e.g. the {{l|zh|京師畯尊}} (銘圖 11784), where it is used as a river name: {{lang|zh|王涉漢伐楚}}.

{{och-l|熯|tr=*n̥ˤanʔ}} (⿱𦰩火) depicts a person bound behind the back, mouth open toward the sky, over fire. It may be related to {{och-l|灘|tr=*n̥ˤar}}, {{och-l|歎|tr=*n̥ˤar}}, {{och-l|嘆|tr=*n̥ˤar}}, {{och-l|熯|tr=*n̥ˤanʔ}}, {{och-l|暵|tr=*n̥ˤanʔ}}, and {{och-l|難|tr=*n̥ˤar}}, in senses connected with drought, burning, or exclamation. From the middle Western Zhou onward, {{l|zh|𦰩}} may have been confused with {{l|zh|黃}}.

The usage for the Chinese ethnicity first appeared during the Northern and Southern Dynasties, claiming the Han dynasty as one of the golden ages of Chinese history.{{rfv-etym|en}} Before the Han dynasty, the Chinese referred their land as [[華夏]] ("Huaxia"), and themselves as [[諸華]] ("various Hua people") or [[諸夏]] ("various people/descendants of the Xias"). "Xia" ("Summer; great, splendid") also gave the name to the first semi-legendary Chinese dynasty, the Xia Dinasty ([[夏朝]]).

